result.execSummary:
The defendant Sarah Marie Parker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Robbery with Use of Force [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Sarah Marie Parker in court with attorney William Joseph Reddin.  Defendant Sarah Marie Parker in custody.  Tyrone Martin St. Junior appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

State has complied with victim notifciation.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, Defense and Defendant.

The Court sentenced the defendant to a TOTAL LENGTH of imprisonment of 7 years, consecutive to any other sentence.
The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons is 4 years with credit for 121 days time served.
The Court orders the defendant to serve a maximum term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 years.

The Court stayed the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 3 years.

Conditions of Probation/Extended Supervision to be determined by the Dept. of Corrections, but to include:
  
*As a condtition of probation, the Court ordered the defendant to serve 7 months in the House of Correction.  FORTHWITH.   The first 2 months: Huber privileges for work, school and treatment.  The last 5 months: Huber privileges for work, school, treatment, The Day Reporting Center and electronic monitoring.
*Mental health assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Alcohol and drug assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Absolute sobriety.
*Random urine screens.  No positive results.
*No illegal drugs.
*No controlled substances without valid prescription.
*No contact with drug community.
*No contact with the victim:  Vigneshwar S., Therese N. and the Co-actors:  Austin Cooper, Michael Dunn.
*Seek and maintain full time employment.
*Cognitive Behavior Therapy.

Restitution is ordered in the amounts of $200.00 to be paid to Therese N. The amount of $3247.20 to be paid to Vigneshwar S., joint and several with Austin Cooper 15CF1531 and Michael Dunn 15CF1532.

- Defendant ordered to submit a DNA sample if not already done.
- Defendant advised that she may never again possess firearms or weapons.
- Civil rights suspended until reinstated.  Order received and filed.
- Pay all costs, fees, restitution and surcharges, including the mandatory DNA surcharge, by DOC out of up to 25% of any applicable prison funds and wages. To be paid by the end of probation.  If not paid, a civil judgment to be entered.
- Defendant does qualify for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program after serving 3 years initial confinement in this case.

The Court does not object to sentence/probation being transferred to Burlington.
